26. tumultuosum (ps) i.e. ‘the tumult (of the sea)'; see on P. 27 and P. 21.

28. orientis (p): contrast cadentis 1. 27.

33. contracta (ps) i.e. ‘the straitening (of the water space)' ; see on P. 26.

34. iactis...molibus is probably an ablative absolute aster the principal verb, as often in Livy. So ll. 30, 31 arbore...culpante.

frequens (ps) is equal to an adverb 3 see P. 31.

36, 37. curn famulis goes, probably, as the position suggests, with both redemptor and dominus.

terrae depends first on dominus, then on fastidiosus. The adjective has stress (see on Odes 4. 9. 26) 3 he is sickand weary of the land, though lord ofit.

39. aerata (p) i.e. ‘for all its bronze plates.' See Gow ad loc. and compare Odes 2. 16. 21. For triremi et see Odes 1. 35. 39.

40. atra (p): see on Odes 2. 14. 23.

41. dolentem...lapis...usus: for the order of dolentem see on P. 51.

Phrygius (p): the order reminds us that it is an expensive imported marble.
